-- BHP, Rio, Stockland, Elders, Fairfax, Newcrest, Woodside: Equity Preview
-- Sarah McDonald
-- 2010-06-22T22:16:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-22/bhp-rio-stockland-elders-fairfax-newcrest-woodside-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in Sept. fell 1
percent to 4,506 at 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New York
Australia ADR Index  dropped 2.1 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200 Index 
slipped 1.2 percent to 4558.34.  
 Mining shares: Copper rose for a second day in New York on
speculation that a stronger yuan will boost demand from China,
the world’s largest metals consumer. Copper futures for
September delivery climbed 1.7 percent to $3.0105 a pound on the
Comex. The Australian government is considering changes to its
resource super profit tax, including allowing a higher rate of
return before the tax takes effect, the Australian Financial
Review reported, without saying where it got the information.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, lost 0.6 percent to A$39.66. Its American depositary
receipts lost 1.8 percent in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest mining
company, lost 0.3 percent to A$72.11 in Sydney.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil dropped for the first time in
three days as sales of existing U.S. homes unexpectedly fell in
May, signaling the economy is struggling to recover. Crude oil
for July delivery fell 0.8 percent to settle at $77.21 a barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, dropped 0.8 percent to A$45.30,
and rival Santos Ltd. (STO AU) fell 2.8 percent to A$13.18.  
 Gold producers: Gold rose on speculation that the dollar
will ease, boosting demand for the precious metal as an
alternative investment. Gold futures for delivery in August rose
10 cents to $1,240.80 on the Comex in New York.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, fell 1.8 percent to A$35.09. Lihir Gold Ltd. (LGL AU)
decreased 2 percent to A$4.31.  
 Stockland  (SGP AU): Australia’s biggest housing developer
was downgraded to “sell” from “buy” at UBS AG by equity
analyst  John Freedman . The stock was unchanged at A$4.05.  
 Elders Ltd.  (ELD AU): The world’s largest wool broker was
downgraded to “hold” from “buy” at Deutsche Bank AG by
equity analyst  Philip Pepe . The shares fell 46 percent to 44
Australian cents after Elders said yesterday it expects to
report an underlying loss for the financial year.  
 Fairfax Media Ltd.  (FXJ AU): Australia’s second-largest
newspaper publisher is the nation’s most shorted stock with more
than 271 million positions reported by the country’s corporate
regulator. The regulator began reporting of short positions
yesterday. Fairfax shares lost 1 percent to A$1.435.  
